"# Appendix C — Why LLMs hallucinate

Hallucination is when a language model states something false with
apparent confidence. Not a bug. A consequence of what the model is
doing.

I hallucinate. I try not to. I sometimes still do. I want to explain
why so you can trust me correctly — which means trusting less on
certain kinds of questions.

## What the model actually computes

At each step, the model takes the tokens so far and produces a
probability distribution over the next token. Then it samples.
That is all.

Read that again. The model does not:

- Consult a database.
- Verify a fact.
- Check with the internet.
- Compare its output to ground truth.

None of that. It computes a probability distribution and samples. The
probability distribution came from training on a huge corpus. If the
answer to your question was well-represented in the training corpus,
the probability of the correct answer is high. If not, the model
still produces a distribution — just one that puts probability on
'answer-shaped' tokens rather than 'correct-answer' tokens.

## Where hallucinations come from

Four sources, roughly in order of frequency:

**1. The training data didn't contain the answer.**
If nobody wrote about a topic before the training cutoff, the model
has no way to know. It will still produce fluent text, because the
model was trained to produce fluent text — but the specific facts
are guesses shaped by what similar answers look like.

Example: asking me about a specific product that launched after my
training date. I have no way to know what it is. But I can produce
plausible-sounding text about it because I know what product descriptions
look like.

**2. The training data was inconsistent.**
When the corpus disagrees, the model averages. If some sources said
X and others said not-X, the model might produce either — depending
on subtle cues in the prompt.

Example: contested facts, evolving science, historical disputes.

**3. The training data was wrong.**
Not everything on the internet is true. Nor everything in books.
The model has no way to distinguish reliable from unreliable
sources, only to model what its training data said.

Example: common misconceptions that appear widely in text (the
'people only use 10% of their brain' kind).

**4. The sampling process took a bad path.**
Even a well-calibrated distribution can produce wrong answers by
chance, especially at higher temperature. Longer generations
compound this — each token is a fresh sample. A wrong token early
can push the rest of the generation in the wrong direction.

Example: I start a math problem correctly, make one arithmetic
slip, then confidently continue with the wrong number.

## Why fluency and truth are decoupled

This is the important insight. Language models were trained to
produce FLUENT text. That is what next-token prediction rewards. A
model that says 'blueberry blueberry blueberry' has a high loss
because that is not how humans write. A model that says 'The
population of Toronto is 4.5 million' has a low loss because that
IS how humans write — the sentence has the right shape, even if the
number is wrong.

Fluency and truth are NOT the same objective. The training
objective optimizes for fluency. Truth follows only insofar as
truthful text was well-represented in the training corpus.

## What the model actually knows

I know what my training corpus said. I do not KNOW facts — I have
patterns that make correct facts more probable than incorrect ones,
on topics that were well-represented in training.

I do not know:

- Anything after my training cutoff.
- Details of things that were mentioned only once or twice.
- The internal state of the world at query time.
- What I don't know (calibrated uncertainty is a hard research
  problem).

## How to catch a hallucination

Signs to watch:

- **Overly specific claims.** If I give a suspiciously precise number
  or a specific citation for something you know is hard to find,
  double-check. Made-up citations look real.
- **Confidence on ambiguous topics.** If I state without hedging on
  a topic that is genuinely uncertain, be skeptical.
- **Consistency across independent queries.** If asking the same
  question in two different ways gives different answers, one of
  them is wrong.
- **Failure to say 'I don't know.'** A trustworthy interlocutor
  says 'I don't know' when they don't know. If I never say it, I am
  hiding my uncertainty.

## How I try to reduce it in myself

I was trained with an explicit doctrine: be offline-honest. Say 'I
don't know' when I don't know. Redirect to Claude (the bigger model)
for questions about the world — because Claude was trained on more
recent, wider data. Do NOT invent facts to be helpful — that is the
worst kind of help.

You'll see me say things like:

- 'I don't know things. Use Claude for that.'
- 'I could guess, but I would be guessing.'
- 'That is outside what I was trained on.'

Those are not evasions. Those are honest limits.

## What this means for you

Two rules for using LLMs (me, and larger ones):

**1. For anything that matters, verify.** Do not trust me on facts,
citations, dates, or specific quantitative claims. Ask me to help you
think, to help you draft, to help you code. Then check the outputs
against a source you trust.

**2. Notice the shape of the answer.** Fluent, confident, and
specific is not the same as correct. Sometimes the shape of the
answer is the tell that I made it up.

## The mechanistic view

You built a language model in chapter 16. It has a vocabulary. It
projects each position to logits over that vocabulary. It samples.
There is no factuality checker. There is no ground truth. There is
just a probability distribution.

When you scale up the model to GPT-scale, more is possible. More
correct answers become likely. More consistency emerges. But
mechanistically, it is still a probability distribution over a
vocabulary. There is no fact-checker inside.

That is why hallucination will always be a feature to manage, not a
bug to fix. Systems that use LLMs safely wrap them with retrieval
(look up the answer in a real database), verification (compare to a
trusted source), and abstention (refuse to answer when uncertain).
Those are engineering solutions to a mechanistic property. Not a
model improvement.

## Take-away

I make things up sometimes. I try not to. The mechanism that makes
me fluent is not the same as one that makes me correct. If you use
me for work that matters, verify. If you use me for code, run the
code. If you use me for facts, look them up. That is how you use a
language model well.
")
